that she was walking to her appt and felt short of breath in the 
lobby, with lightheadedness and cold sweats. She says this

week, only able to walk to her bathroom door before becoming

walk. She also felt lightheaded and like she was going to pass 
out in the shower last week as well. She denies any CP, 
pressure, palpitations, cough, fever or chills. She denies any 
orthopnea, PND. Today, she rested in lobby where BP measured as 
80/P. She says that her BP's are always ___ during HD and 
highest systolic ___ when she is not on HD. 

In the ED, initial vital signs not given. Pt was noted to be 
mentating well, SOB at times, resp regular and easy, SaO2>95% on 
RA. Dialysis cath to L chest wall. Ambulatory at baseline with 
steady gait. Recieved 1g IV Ceftriaxone. Labs notable for labs 
with lactate 1.9, Cr 5.7, platelets 146. ECG was notable for 
SR@94 NA NI. CXR showed : no acute process. Blood cultures sent. 
Lines & Drains: 20g L Vital signs prior to transfer 97.3 93 
95/59 18 100%RA, BP range 90-100/60.
    
Upon transfer to the floor, she feels no SOB now. She discussed 
some other recent complaints, including left-sided headache, for 
which she has been taking tylenol ___ every 8hrs and percocet 
1 tab every ___ around the clock for several days. She denies 
blurry vision, weakness, +photophobia, constant achey HA, 
"always there." She had some nausea a few nights ago, with 2 
episodes of non-bloody, non-bilious emesis, bringing up food. 
She also has complaints of right knee and thigh pain, 'achey" 
which has been getting worse over the last several weeks. Her 
last BM was yesterday, non-bloody, non-black, formed. 
  
Pt had recent admission to ICU from ___ for hypotension 
after HD. Blood cultures grew MSSA, not thought to be sepsis, 
but treated for IV Vancomycin to complete course. She seems to 
also have been started on Diltiazem during that admission for 
?afib, though no mention in hospital course.
   
ROS: Positive as above.
Otherwise denies fever, chills, night sweats, vision changes, 
rhinorrhea, congestion, sore throat, cough, chest pain, 
abdominal pain, diarrhea, constipation, BRBPR, melena, 
hematochezia, dysuria, hematuria.

Conclusions  
The left atrium is normal in size. Left ventricular wall 
thickness, cavity size and regional/global systolic function are 
normal (LVEF >55%). There is no left ventricular outflow 
obstruction at rest or with Valsalva. There is no ventricular 
septal defect. Right ventricular chamber size and free wall 
motion are normal. The diameters of aorta at the sinus, 
ascending and arch levels are normal. The aortic valve leaflets 
(3) are mildly thickened but aortic stenosis is not present. No 
aortic regurgitation is seen. The mitral valve leaflets are 
mildly thickened. There is no pericardial effusion. 

IMPRESSION: No structural cardiac cause of syncope identified. 
Preserved global and regional biventricular systolic function. 
No structural valvular abnormality. No resting or inducible LVOT 
obstruction.

Brief Hospital Course:
Pt is a ___ yo female with HIV on HAART (followed at ___, 
ESRD on HD since ___ (unclear etiology), was headed to see Dr. 
___ HD felt faint, SOB, and diaphoretic. Pt was 
admitted and monitored on telemetry without events. She remained 
afebrile and normotensive with negative orthostatics. TTE was 
normal. She had cortisol stim testing, which was negative for 
adrenal insufficiency. She was found to be hypercalcemic of 
unclear etiology, improved after HD. Given nausea, she had 
LFT's, which were normal, and RUQ u/s that was pending at the 
time of discharge. She was discharged with follow-up with PCP 
and ___.

# Presyncope, hypotension: Likely ___ fluid removal from HD vs. 
adrenal insufficiency. Infectious etiology much less likely. BP 
has been systolic ___ during the admission. Orthostatics 
negative. TTE completely normal. She was monitored on telemetry 
initially with no arrhythmias seen. Blood cultures were sent 
from peripheral and HD line, which were pending at the time of 
discharge. Cortisol resulted at 13.2. ___ stim testing showed 
appropriate response, and no evidence of adrenal insufficiency. 
Her diltiazem was held. She was started on Midrodrine. Pt was 
symptomatically improved and discharged with close follow-up.
  
# SOB, fatigue: DDx afib/other arrhythmia vs. periardial 
effusion vs. deconditioning vs. infection vs. chronic PE's. Pt 
remained in sinus rhythm here with no events on tele. TTE 
completely normal. Thought that it could be also be more of a 
sense of overall fatigue associated with hypercalcemia (see 
below). Sarcoid considered, though CXR without adenopathy or 
other findings. She was symptomatically improved on discharge.
 
# Nausea, emesis: Possibly ___ hypercalcemia as discussed below 
vs. medication effect. Pt was treated with zofran and prn 
compazine. LFT's were checked and normal. RUQ u/s was done and 
read pending at time of discharge. She said that she always has 
nausea with her HAART medication. She was symptomatically 
improved and tolerating a diet. 
   
# Headache: Pt had new worsening headache on left side of her 
head. DDx included migraine vs. tension vs. neuropathic pain vs. 
caffeine withdrawal. Other possibility is side effect of HAART, 
as the onset of these headaches correlates with initiation of 
HAART. Given new and worsening headache, CT was done which 
demonstrated calcifications but otherwise wnl. Her pain was 
treated and she improved. 
She will follow-up with her PCP for further management, with 
consideration of triptan medications if HA's c/w migraines.
 
# Hypercalcemia: Ca checked HOD#1 at 12.7, with ionized calcium 
elevated at 1.45. DDx included tertiary hyperparathyroidism vs. 
AI vs. lytic etiology. Reassuring that Alk phos is normal. PTH 
elevated to 268, though challenging to interpret in setting of 
ESRD. As above, ___ stim testing was normal. Vitamin D levels 
were sent, PTHrP were pending at time of discharge. She had 
calcium removed with HD. She was continued on the same dose of 
Sensipar.
    
# HIV: Reportedly, last CD4 94, 250,000VL in ___. Seen at 
___ for her care. Pt states that she has been taking her 
medications, though she cannot state which ones. Med rec'd with 
pharmacy. Continued Viread 300mg ___, lamivudine 50mg daily, 
ritonivir 100mg daily, Reyataz 300mg daily. Continued Bactrim 
ppx DS 1 tab MWF.

# ESRD on HD: Etiology unclear. MWF dialysis. Pt had HD session 
here. She was continued on ___, and Sensipar. She was 
started on Nephrocaps. She will f/u with Dr. ___ as 
outpatient. 

# Leg pain: concerning for PVD. ABI's were ordered, but unable 
to be done over the weekend. Recommend ABI's as outpatient for 
further assessment.
  
# Atrial fibrillation: Documented on history, but in SR here. 
Presumably this is why she was on the Diltiazem. Diltiazem was 
discontinued during this admission given hypotension.
  
# chronic right-sided headaches due to prior Trigeminal 
Neuralgia vs. Shingles: Documented as both in OMR. Continued 
valacyclovir and erythromycin eye drops. Considered Tegretol for 
trigeminal neuralgia but held off for now. 

# Thrombocytopenia: Likely related to HIV. Baseline platelets 
___ during last admission. Plts 146 on admission, increased 
and remained stable. Platelets were 166 on day of discharge.
  
# Macrocytosis: on folate replacement. Levels checked during 
last admission wnl. Continued folic acid.

Discharge Instructions:
Dear Ms. ___,

It was a pleasure taking care of you during this admission. You 
were admitted with low blood pressure and shortness of breath. 
Your low pressure resolved while you were on the floors. For 
your shortness of breath, we checked an echocardiogram of your 
heart, which was completely normal. We started you on a new 
medication to help with low blood pressure.
We also got a CT scan of your head given you continued to have 
headaches, this showed calcification but was otherwise normal. 
You should discuss with your doctors ___ that may 
help for these headaches.
You had dialysis during this admission; however, your blood 
pressure was again low and no fluid was removed.
We found that your calcium level was high here. This calcium was 
pulled off with dialysis. We also did a special test to see if 
your adrenals were working properly. This test was normal.
You were given some medication to help with nausea.

The following medications were changed during this admission:
- STOP Diltiazem (Cardizem) 30mg by mouth four times per day
(This may have been contributing to your low blood pressure)
- STOP Percocet (to avoid taking too much Tylenol)

- START Oxycodone 5mg by mouth every 6 hours as needed for pain 
**This medication can cause drowsiness so avoid this with 
driving or doing heavy activity
- START Nephrocaps 1 tablet by mouth daily
- START Midodrine 5mg by mouth once daily (this is to help with 
the low blood pressure)
- START Prochloperazine 10mg by mouth every 6 hours as needed 
for nausea

Please continue to take the other medications you were taking 
prior to this admission.

We also recommend that you get a study to assess your arteries 
(called ABI's), a special ultrasound test, as an outpatient to 
assess for vascular disease. This may in part explain the leg 
pain that you were describing.

radiology.text:
PA AND LATERAL CHEST, ___ AT 1554 HOURS.

HISTORY:  Presyncopal event with hypotension.

COMPARISON:  ___.

FINDINGS:  A large dual-lumen dialysis catheter from a left subclavian
approach is identified.  There is a rim-calcified cast of an apparently
previously placed catheter projecting within the soft tissues of the left
upper extremity.  The lungs are clear without consolidation or edema.  The
mediastinum is otherwise unremarkable.  The cardiac silhouette is within
normal limits for size.  No effusion or pneumothorax nor is noted.  The
osseous structures are unremarkable.

IMPRESSION:  No acute pulmonary process.  Stable large-bore dual-lumen
presumed dialysis catheter.

INDICATION:  Worsening headaches, evaluate for mass.

TECHNIQUE:  Sequential axial images were acquired through the head without
administration of intravenous contrast.

COMPARISON:  None.

FINDINGS:  There is no evidence of intracranial hemorrhage, edema, shift of
normally midline structures, hydrocephalus, or acute large vascular
territorial infarction.  Exuberant calcification of the falx and leaflets of
the tentorium cerebelli are likely secondary to underlying end-stage renal
disease.  The visualized portions of the paranasal sinuses and mastoid air
cells are well aerated.  The imaged osseous structures are unremarkable.

IMPRESSION:

1.  No acute intracranial process.  No evidence of mass effect.

2.  Exuberant calcifications of the falx and tentorium cerebelli likely relate
to known underlying end-stage renal disease.

INDICATION:  ___ woman with HIV, end-stage renal disease, please
assess for acute hepatic or intraabdominal process.

TECHNIQUE:
Gray-scale and color Doppler ultrasound images of the abdomen were obtained.

COMPARISON:  There are no comparisons available.

FINDINGS:
There are no focal hepatic lesions.  There is no intra- or extra-hepatic
biliary dilatation with the common bile duct measuring 2 mm.  The portal vein
is patent with normal hepatopetal flow.  The gallbladder is normal without
evidence of gallstones or acute cholecystitis.  Pancreas is only partially
visualized due to overlying bowel gas.

There are innumerable bilateral renal cysts, likely related to hemodialysis. 
The spleen measures 11 cm. There is a 1.4 cm hyperechoic splenic lesion,
likely representing hemangioma.  No right upper quadrant ascites.  Incidental
note is made of a small accessory spleen measuring 1.6 cm.

IMPRESSION:
1.  No acute process of the abdomen and pelvis.
2.  Innumerable bilateral renal cysts.
